																		Re: Tale: A Hymn For Pandora
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/oricat" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5199638); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=5199638&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252511" alt="OriCat" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=5199638)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/oricat" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5199638); return false;" >OriCat</a></span> <span class="odate time_1557676028 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 May 2019 15:47</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4246590">
									

<p>I don't know if you're looking for a more senior critiquer, but I'll give you a look over anyway.</p>
<p>To make sure that I have got the general overview right: This is a general announcement of the opening of clearance to everyone in the Foundation. Thematically, it's supposed to be relatively humanist, to affirm to the researchers that even though the world is full of all these horrors the Foundation is victorious and will continue to be. Is that what you were going for?</p>
<p>Line-by-line:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Guide:<br />
<span style="text-decoration: line-through;">strikethrough</span>: remove<br />
<strong>bold</strong>: insert</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Greeting<strong>s</strong>, Site-17 personnel.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>In the second-person greetings is plural.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Today, it is my great privilege to deliver news to you that should never have needed delivering.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This sentence kind of sounds awkward. I think I get what you <em>mean</em> - everything should have been open from the first so they're kind of apologizing for not opening clearance earlier - but it comes across more regretful. Maybe something about how &quot;this announcement should have been made much earlier&quot; would sell the right connotations.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>discomforting</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Maybe &quot;disquieting&quot; would be a better word here?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>they will <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">serve to</span> better facilitate a smoothly-operating Foundation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Redundant.</p>
<p>This first paragraph should also contain some kind of suggestion that a paradigm shift in Foundation operating procedure has occurred, and that it's not just an announcement of (for example) someone's death or promotion, which won't affect the lower researchers.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>who <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">had come</span><strong>came</strong> together</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You don't need the past perfect here, just the past.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Their</strong> Discoveries, at first</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Makes it clearer that we are still talking about Foundation history.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>slugs which excreted ranch dressing, <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">a</span> probability-defying coin<strong>s</strong>, living pencils</p>
</blockquote>
<p>For parallelism purposes, these should all be either plural or singular.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>… <strong>but</strong> then<strong>,</strong> they began to discover monsters</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Sounds a little more natural with the conjunction.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Things that burned through metal and flesh,</p>
</blockquote>
<p>What kind of things? That's kind of vague.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>predators that could fall to neither bullet nor missile</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&quot;Predators neither bullet nor missile could harm&quot; is the more active form.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>millennia of earth and stone</p>
</blockquote>
<p>While to geologists it is perfectly intuitive that rock is time, to most people, it isn't. &quot;Trapped for millennia in earth and stone&quot; would make it slightly less jarring.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Soon<strong>,</strong> the discovery of these aberrations outnumbered the innocuous,</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You are having &quot;outnumbered&quot; apply to &quot;discovery&quot;, an uncountable noun. You could either say that the rate of discovery of malignant anomalies outstripped the rate of the innocuous discovery, or that the malignant anomalies outnumbered innocuous ones (without &quot;discovery&quot; in there at all).</p>
<blockquote>
<p>the <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">nature of what the</span> Foundation<strong>'s nature</strong> <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">was</span></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Redundant words.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Casualties became <strong>only</strong>a number on paper<strong>,</strong> and mercenaries were consulted, prior to the formation of any true Mobile Task Force.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Were they only consulted, or actually hired?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The O5s will not tell you about the days anomalies were the benign and the playful. I don't think any of us can blame them for that omission.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This would be a delightful place to add a semicolon. And adding some kind of tag before &quot;the O5s&quot; - something like &quot;In the face of this reality&quot; would help the flow a bit.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The truth of the Foundation is built on lies.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&#8230;then how is it a truth? Did you mean something like &quot;The truth is, the Foundation is built on lies&quot;?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>they <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">can</span><strong>will</strong> tell you</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Stronger.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>other-world heels</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&quot;Otherworldly&quot; is the adjectival form.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>You need not feel the obligation to read them all at once.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&#8230;I am pretty sure nobody was feeling that obligation. It takes away the gravitas here. Another sentence or two about what they can now read - e.g. &quot;You have access to a catalogue of information no less than the Directors&quot; or &quot;may see every anomaly we have ever contained&quot; would be a good replacement and drive home exactly what it is they're getting here.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>chaos: <strong>t</strong>hat</p>
</blockquote>
<p>No capitalization after colons.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>more cruel</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Crueler is a real word.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The human species is surrounded by death, and more of it day by day.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&#8230;what does this really mean? Yeah, 93% of everybody who has ever been alive is now dead, but so? You've been doing great with the <a href="https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CosmicHorrorStory">Cosmic Horror Story</a> in every other sentence, so this one just feels a little&#8230; drab by comparison.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>next to <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">nothing</span><strong>zero</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Probabilities are given numerically.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>There exists a universe, somewhere, where the colors red and green have mingled and born two children to the stars, Malice and Chaos, who once fled their natal nest and tore through time itself. Around their home lie graveyards, piled on top of schools with classes who all graduated in 1976, piled on top of Scarlet bones and waste. And in that graveyard, two riders did approach a monument of smoldering, red-flecked ash, and read allowed the words of an author long deceased.</p>
<p>“Look around you, mortal men, and see the land of gods, and weep. We were once the strange and the disquieting, the horrific and the dead. We were anomalies, but anomalies no more.”</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I don't understand these entire two paragraphs. Would the Site-17 personnel all understand them either, if they haven't yet got the clearance to look at the pages detailing these anomalies? Really, this part you could take out, and the flow might be better for it - straight from despair to hope.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>armed tooth and nail</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Mixed metaphors. You can be &quot;Armed to the teeth&quot;, or you can &quot;fight tooth and nail&quot;, whichever you prefer, but not both.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>We are the Foundation. We will secure, we will contain, and we will protect above all else; we are the Foundation, and our mission is unstoppable.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That's two &quot;we are the Foundation&quot;s very close to each other. It's sounding very much like a mantra, but if that's not what you were going for then take one out.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<br />
Ultimately, I like it an awful lot though! Your tone stays nice and consistent throughout, and the ideas mostly flow from one to the next in a logical way. The idea of the Director giving what is essentially a lit review to the researchers to explain this sudden new clearance makes a lot of sense.
							</div>

								
					
